### dispatch-service local exercise file
# REST Client (VS Code) — runs every endpoint of the service.
# Boot the server first: `npm run dev` (loads .env via tsx --env-file).
#
# NOTE on paths: the service mounts its routes under `/v1` (`/v1/dispatch/...`).
# The gateway is pass-through — it forwards `/v1/dispatch/...` UNCHANGED — so the
# path is identical whether you hit dispatch-service DIRECTLY (this file) or via
# the gateway. Health checks (`/healthz`, `/readyz`) stay unprefixed.
#
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# THE BIG DIFFERENCE FROM order-service: there is NO HTTP endpoint that
# creates an assignment. An assignment is born when dispatch CONSUMES an
# `order.created` event, and a driver only gets offered if the pool has a
# free driver (fed by `driver.availability.changed` events). So to exercise
# the HTTP surface you FIRST publish two events via the RabbitMQ UI (see the
# "Drive an assignment into existence" block), THEN call accept/reject/get.
#
# PREREQUISITES:
#
#   1. Postgres + Redis + RabbitMQ. `docker compose up -d` brings up the dev
#      Postgres (:5437) + a Redis. RabbitMQ must be reachable at RABBITMQ_URL —
#      the platform's `logistics-rabbitmq` (dev/dev creds) is likely already
#      running (`docker ps`); set RABBITMQ_URL=amqp://dev:dev@localhost:5672.
#      (If you use the platform RabbitMQ + Redis, you don't need the compose
#       Redis — see .env.example's note on the 6379 vs 6380 host port.)
#
#   2. User JWTs signed with JWT_SECRET. dispatch VERIFIES the inbound token
#      with JWT_SECRET (= auth-service's AUTH_JWT_SECRET); it does NOT mint
#      tokens. It only needs `sub` + `role` (HS256). Self-mint:
#        # a DRIVER token — sub MUST equal the driverId you make available below
#        node -e 'const jwt=require("jsonwebtoken"); console.log(jwt.sign({sub:"04940000-0000-7000-8000-000000000d01", role:"driver"}, process.env.JWT_SECRET, {algorithm:"HS256", expiresIn:"30m"}))'
#        # an ADMIN token
#        node -e 'const jwt=require("jsonwebtoken"); console.log(jwt.sign({sub:"05940000-0000-7000-8000-0000000admin", role:"admin"}, process.env.JWT_SECRET, {algorithm:"HS256", expiresIn:"30m"}))'
#      Run from this repo so jsonwebtoken + JWT_SECRET resolve, e.g.
#        export $(grep -v '^#' .env | xargs) && node -e '...'
#
#   3. force-assign (admin) VALIDATES the driver via a service-JWT call to
#      `GET {DISPATCH_USER_SERVICE_URL}/v1/users/internal/drivers/{id}`. To get
#      a 204 (not 422), that endpoint must return the driver. Two ways:
#        A. Run user-service alongside, seed a driver, set DISPATCH_USER_SERVICE_URL
#           to it (and dispatch's SERVICE_JWT_SECRET = user-service's secret).
#        B. Run a tiny stub that serves /v1/users/internal/drivers/:id (see the
#           integration test helper `tests/integration/helpers/user-service-driver-stub.ts`).
#      accept/reject/get do NOT need user-service — only force-assign + the
#      drivers/available enrichment do.
#
#   4. The OFFER expires after DISPATCH_OFFER_TTL_SECONDS (default 30). If you
#      don't POST /accept within the TTL, the offer expires (via the TTL+DLX
#      holding queue) and the order re-parks to awaiting_driver. Set a short
#      DISPATCH_OFFER_TTL_SECONDS to watch this quickly.
#
# Usage:
#   1. Paste a driver JWT into @driverToken (its sub = @driverId) and an admin
#      JWT into @adminToken.
#   2. Publish the two events in "Drive an assignment into existence" (RabbitMQ
#      UI). Use @orderId / @driverId as the ids in those envelopes.
#   3. Click "Send Request" on the HTTP calls below.

@host = http://localhost:3004
@contentType = application/json

# The driver you'll make available + offer to. @driverToken's `sub` MUST equal this.
@driverId = 04940000-0000-7000-8000-000000000d01

# A SECOND driver (for force-assign / wrong-driver probes). Must be resolvable by
# user-service/stub (prereq #3) for force-assign to 204 instead of 422.
@driverId2 = 04940000-0000-7000-8000-000000000d02

# The order you'll publish in `order.created`. You choose this id; reference it everywhere.
@orderId = 06940000-0000-7000-8000-00000000a001

# Paste valid user JWTs (see prereq #2 — node one-liner self-mints them).
@driverToken = <paste DRIVER JWT (role = driver, sub = @driverId)>
@adminToken  = <paste ADMIN JWT (role = admin)>


############################################################
# Health
############################################################

### healthz — liveness (always 200)
GET {{host}}/healthz

### readyz — readiness (200 when Postgres + RabbitMQ channel + Redis are healthy)
GET {{host}}/readyz


############################################################
# Drive an assignment into existence — publish via RabbitMQ UI
#   (http://localhost:15672, login dev/dev) → exchange `logistics.events`
############################################################
#
# dispatch is event-driven: it has NO "create assignment" HTTP endpoint. Publish
# these two envelopes to exchange `logistics.events` with the routing keys below.
# Use @driverId / @orderId as the ids. After publishing, GET the assignment
# (admin) to watch awaiting_driver → offered.
#
# ────── STEP 1: make a driver available  (adds @driverId to the FIFO pool) ──────
# Routing key: driver.availability.changed
# Body:  (NOTE: the field is `userId`, NOT driverId — it's the driver's user id)
# {
#   "eventId": "07940000-0000-7000-8000-aaaaaaaaaaaa",
#   "eventType": "driver.availability.changed",
#   "eventVersion": "1.0.0",
#   "occurredAt": "2026-06-09T00:00:00Z",
#   "correlationId": "smoke-1",
#   "producer": "user-service",
#   "data": { "userId": "04940000-0000-7000-8000-000000000d01", "isAvailable": true, "changedAt": "2026-06-09T00:00:00Z" }
# }
#
# ────── STEP 2: place an order  (creates the assignment + offers to the driver) ──────
# Routing key: order.created
# Body:
# {
#   "eventId": "07940000-0000-7000-8000-bbbbbbbbbbbb",
#   "eventType": "order.created",
#   "eventVersion": "1.0.0",
#   "occurredAt": "2026-06-09T00:01:00Z",
#   "correlationId": "smoke-2",
#   "producer": "order-service",
#   "data": {
#     "orderId": "06940000-0000-7000-8000-00000000a001",
#     "customerId": "47913fd3-7bf9-4182-9d94-6144ddb74cfe",
#     "pickup":  { "label": "Warehouse 3", "street": "12 Dock Rd", "city": "Manila", "country": "PH", "lat": 14.5547, "lng": 120.9772 },
#     "dropoff": { "street": "9 Ayala Ave", "city": "Makati", "country": "PH", "lat": 14.5547, "lng": 121.0244 },
#     "items": [ { "description": "Sealed parcel", "quantity": 2 } ],
#     "scheduledFor": null
#   }
# }
#
# After STEP 2, GET the assignment → status "offered", currentAttempt.driverId = @driverId.
# Don't accept within DISPATCH_OFFER_TTL_SECONDS → it expires → back to awaiting_driver.


############################################################
# Read the assignment
############################################################

### Current offer for the authenticated driver
# 204 = no outstanding offer; 200 = { orderId, offerAttempts, expiresAt, order: { pickup, dropoff, items } }
GET {{host}}/v1/dispatch/offers/current
Authorization: Bearer {{driverToken}}

### Admin reads any assignment by orderId
GET {{host}}/v1/dispatch/assignments/{{orderId}}
Authorization: Bearer {{adminToken}}

### The OFFERED driver reads their assignment (admin OR the involved driver only)
GET {{host}}/v1/dispatch/assignments/{{orderId}}
Authorization: Bearer {{driverToken}}


############################################################
# Accept / reject the offer (driver)
############################################################

### Driver ACCEPTS the current offer → 204, status becomes assigned, publishes dispatch.driver.assigned
# The driver JWT `sub` must equal the currently-offered driver (@driverId).
POST {{host}}/v1/dispatch/assignments/{{orderId}}/accept
Authorization: Bearer {{driverToken}}

### Driver REJECTS the current offer → 204, back to awaiting_driver, frees the driver, re-attempts
# (reason optional). Re-publish STEP 1 for another driver to see the re-offer.
POST {{host}}/v1/dispatch/assignments/{{orderId}}/reject
Authorization: Bearer {{driverToken}}
Content-Type: {{contentType}}

{
  "reason": "too far"
}


############################################################
# Admin force-assign + available drivers
############################################################

### Admin force-assigns a driver to an unassigned/parked/failed order → 204, status assigned
# Requires @driverId2 to be resolvable via user-service/stub (prereq #3), else 422.
# Only allowed from awaiting_driver or failed (NOT offered/assigned/completed/cancelled).
POST {{host}}/v1/dispatch/assignments/{{orderId}}/force-assign
Authorization: Bearer {{adminToken}}
Content-Type: {{contentType}}

{
  "driverId": "{{driverId2}}"
}

### Admin lists currently-available drivers (enriched from user-service)
GET {{host}}/v1/dispatch/drivers/available
Authorization: Bearer {{adminToken}}


############################################################
# Free a busy driver — publish via RabbitMQ UI (exchange logistics.events)
############################################################
#
# Once a driver is `assigned`, these events free them back into the pool and
# re-dispatch parked orders. GET /v1/dispatch/drivers/available after to confirm.
#
# ────── delivery.completed  (driver finished → freed, order completed) ──────
# Routing key: delivery.completed
# Body:
# {
#   "eventId": "07940000-0000-7000-8000-cccccccccccc",
#   "eventType": "delivery.completed",
#   "eventVersion": "1.0.0",
#   "occurredAt": "2026-06-09T00:30:00Z",
#   "correlationId": "smoke-3",
#   "producer": "tracking-service",
#   "data": { "orderId": "06940000-0000-7000-8000-00000000a001" }
# }
#
# ────── order.cancelled  (order cancelled → driver freed if any) ──────
# Routing key: order.cancelled
# Body:
# {
#   "eventId": "07940000-0000-7000-8000-dddddddddddd",
#   "eventType": "order.cancelled",
#   "eventVersion": "1.0.0",
#   "occurredAt": "2026-06-09T00:10:00Z",
#   "correlationId": "smoke-4",
#   "producer": "order-service",
#   "data": { "orderId": "06940000-0000-7000-8000-00000000a001", "customerId": "47913fd3-7bf9-4182-9d94-6144ddb74cfe", "previousStatus": "assigned", "reason": "customer changed mind" }
# }
#
# Idempotency probe: publish the SAME envelope twice (same eventId) — the second
# is a no-op (processed_events dedups; driver not double-freed).


############################################################
# Negative-path probes (intentionally fail; for spot-checking error shapes)
############################################################

### No auth — expect 401 unauthorized
GET {{host}}/v1/dispatch/assignments/{{orderId}}

### Bogus JWT — expect 401 unauthorized
GET {{host}}/v1/dispatch/assignments/{{orderId}}
Authorization: Bearer not.a.real.jwt

### Accept by a driver who is NOT the offered driver — expect 403 forbidden
# Use a driver JWT whose sub != the currently-offered @driverId.
POST {{host}}/v1/dispatch/assignments/{{orderId}}/accept
Authorization: Bearer <paste a DIFFERENT driver's JWT (role=driver, sub != @driverId)>

### Accept when the order is NOT offered (e.g. already assigned, or awaiting) — expect 409 conflict
POST {{host}}/v1/dispatch/assignments/{{orderId}}/accept
Authorization: Bearer {{driverToken}}

### Accept with a CUSTOMER-role JWT — expect 403 (role guard: drivers only)
POST {{host}}/v1/dispatch/assignments/{{orderId}}/accept
Authorization: Bearer <paste a CUSTOMER JWT (role = customer)>

### force-assign by a NON-admin (driver) — expect 403 forbidden
POST {{host}}/v1/dispatch/assignments/{{orderId}}/force-assign
Authorization: Bearer {{driverToken}}
Content-Type: {{contentType}}

{ "driverId": "{{driverId2}}" }

### force-assign an UNKNOWN driver (not in user-service/stub) — expect 422 unprocessable_entity
POST {{host}}/v1/dispatch/assignments/{{orderId}}/force-assign
Authorization: Bearer {{adminToken}}
Content-Type: {{contentType}}

{ "driverId": "04940000-0000-7000-8000-0000000dead0" }

### force-assign with a non-uuid driverId — expect 400 validation_failed
POST {{host}}/v1/dispatch/assignments/{{orderId}}/force-assign
Authorization: Bearer {{adminToken}}
Content-Type: {{contentType}}

{ "driverId": "not-a-uuid" }

### force-assign an already-assigned order — expect 409 conflict
# Drive the order to assigned first (accept), then run this.
POST {{host}}/v1/dispatch/assignments/{{orderId}}/force-assign
Authorization: Bearer {{adminToken}}
Content-Type: {{contentType}}

{ "driverId": "{{driverId2}}" }

### GET an assignment as an UNRELATED driver (not the offered/assigned one) — expect 403 forbidden
GET {{host}}/v1/dispatch/assignments/{{orderId}}
Authorization: Bearer <paste an UNRELATED driver's JWT>

### GET a nonexistent assignment (admin) — expect 404 not_found
GET {{host}}/v1/dispatch/assignments/06940000-0000-7000-8000-00000000ffff
Authorization: Bearer {{adminToken}}

### List available drivers as a NON-admin (driver) — expect 403 forbidden
GET {{host}}/v1/dispatch/drivers/available
Authorization: Bearer {{driverToken}}
